body:
### Describe the bug
```
⮞ gh --version
gh version 2.4.0 (1980-01-01)
https://github.com/cli/cli/releases/tag/v2.4.0
```

When authenticating `gh` with github, the flow writes to `config.yml`, not just `hosts.yml`. I believe this is to set `git_protocol` (possibly there are other reasons I'm unaware of). Unfortunately this prevents users of [`home-manager`](https://github.com/nix-community/home-manager) (In short, software for managing system configuration in a reproducible manner), from allowing it to manage their `gh` configuration. This is because when `home-manager` is used to provide the config, `config.yml` becomes a symlink to an immutable file in the nix store. Therefore, the auth flow is unable to write to it.

Feel free to take a look at [the home-manager issue](https://github.com/nix-community/home-manager/issues/1654) for more context. 

I'm aware this is a somewhat niche use case. Notwithstanding, would it be possible to alter `gh auth login` to not require write access to `config.yml`, but instead only write to `hosts.yml`? It seems like if `gh` detects an existing config, then it ought not need to write to it.

Any thoughts on the feasibility of this change would be welcome!

### Steps to reproduce the behavior

1. Install nix and home-manager
2. Create `~/.config/nixpkgs/home.nix` containing the following
```
{ config, pkgs, ... }:

{
  programs.home-manager.enable = true;
  home.username = "myusername";
  home.homeDirectory = "/home/myusername";
  home.stateVersion = "21.05";
  programs.gh = {
    enable = true;
    settings = {
      git_protocol = "ssh";
    };
  };
}
```
4. build the config using the command `home-manager switch`. This will install `gh`, and generate a `config.yml`, both of which will be symlinks to non-writable files in the nix store. The file linked to by `config.yml` will contain the `git_protocol: ssh` setting.
3. `gh auth login` will fail when it tries to write to `config.yml`

### Expected vs actual behavior

- Expected: when authenticating with `gh auth login`, `gh` only requires write access to `hosts.yml`, enabling reproducible automatic configuration management.
- Actual: `gh` fails to authenticate if `config.yml` is not writable.
